"1155":"1155","02/08/1222":"2 August 1222","3 avril 1211":"3 April 1211","environ 1206":"about 1206","about 1130":"about 1130","Toulouse, Haute-Garonne, Midi-Pyrénées, France":"Toulouse, Haute-Garonne, France","Saint-Gilles, Département du Gard, Languedoc-Roussillon":"Saint-Gilles, Nîmes, Gard, Languedoc-Roussillon, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"TOULOUSE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Monique, Camile, Emile, Gilles, Marcel, Rosaire.","French and English: habitational name from Toulouse, the name of several places in the southwestern part of France, most notably the city in Haute-Garonne, the capital of this French department and of the region of Occitanie."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Laurence","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French form of Latin <i>Laurentius</i> ‘man from Laurentum’. <i>Laurentum</i> was a town in Latium, which may have got its name from Latin <i>laurus</i> ‘laurel’, although it is more probably of pre-Roman origin. The given name was moderately popular in the Middle Ages (when it was used for girls as well as boys), under the influence of a 3rd-century saint who was one of the seven deacons of Rome. He was martyred in  258 . The legend is that, having been required to hand over the Church's treasures to the civil authorities, he assembled the poor and sick and presented them. For this act of Christian defiance, he was roasted to death on a gridiron. In England the name is also associated with  St Laurence of Canterbury  (  d. 619 ). A more recent influence has been the actor  Sir Laurence Olivier  (  1907–89 ).  See also  Lawrence ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Laurence de TOULOUSE was born about 1130, in Saint-Gilles, Nîmes, Gard, Languedoc-Roussillon, France. She married comte Bernard III dit Dodon de Comminges in 1150. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died on 2 August 1222, in Toulouse, Haute-Garonne, France, at the age of 93."},"et":{"about 1130–02/08/1222":"umbes 1130–2. august 1222","1120–1181":"1120–1181","1152–1225":"1152–1225","1155–1206":"1155–1206","1155–1211":"1155–1211","1130–1222":"1130–1222","environ 1155":"umbes 1155","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1181":"1181","1206":"1206","1225":"1225","1222":"1222","1211":"1211","1155":"1155","02/08/1222":"2. august 1222","3 avril 1211":"3. aprill 1211","environ 1206":"umbes 1206","about 1130":"umbes 1130","Toulouse, Haute-Garonne, Midi-Pyrénées, France":"Toulouse, Haute-Garonne, Prantsusmaa","Saint-Gilles, Département du Gard, Languedoc-Roussillon":"Saint-Gilles, Nîmes, Gard, Languedoc-Roussillon, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1130–02/08/1222":"noin 1130–2. elokuuta 1222","1120–1181":"1120–1181","1152–1225":"1152–1225","1155–1206":"1155–1206","1155–1211":"1155–1211","1130–1222":"1130–1222","environ 1155":"noin 1155","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1181":"1181","1206":"1206","1225":"1225","1222":"1222","1211":"1211","1155":"1155","02/08/1222":"2. elokuuta 1222","3 avril 1211":"3. huhtikuuta 1211","environ 1206":"noin 1206","about 1130":"noin 1130","Toulou